    {
      "id": "doc-0-chunk-1",
      "document_id": "falls-prevention",
      "title": "Older adult fall prevention",
      "source": "CDC Older Adult Fall Prevention",
      "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/falls/about/index.html",
      "text": "ention\nKeywords: \u8dcc\u5012, \u6454\u5012, \u8d70\u8def\u4e0d\u7a69, \u982d\u6688, \u9aa8\u6298, \u649e\u5230\u982d, \u9577\u8005\u5b89\u5168, fall, falls, fracture, balance\nContent: Falls are common among adults age 65 and older, but many falls can be prevented. Helpful steps include removing home hazards, improving lighting, checking vision, reviewing medicines with a clinician or pharmacist, and doing strength and balance activities when appropriate. After a fall, urgent medical care is important if there is head injury, confusion, inability to stand, suspected fracture, severe pain, heavy bleeding, or anticoagulant use.",
