    {
      "id": "doc-1-chunk-1",
      "document_id": "emergency-warning-signs",
      "title": "Emergency warning signs for adults",
      "source": "MedlinePlus When to use the emergency room - adult",
      "url": "https://medlineplus.gov/ency/patientinstructions/000593.htm",
      "text": "\u98a8, \u62bd\u6410, \u610f\u8b58\u6df7\u4e82, \u5927\u91cf\u51fa\u8840, emergency, chest pain, shortness of breath, stroke, confusion\nContent: Use emergency care for symptoms that may threaten life or cause permanent harm. Warning signs include severe chest pain or pressure, severe trouble breathing, fainting, sudden one-sided weakness or facial droop, sudden trouble speaking, seeing, walking, or understanding, head injury followed by fainting or confusion, seizure that lasts longer than about one minute or is followed by slow recovery, heavy bleeding, severe allergic reaction with breathing problems, and suspected fracture with inability to move.",
