    {
      "id": "doc-2-chunk-1",
      "document_id": "medicine-fall-risk",
      "title": "Medicines and fall risk in older adults",
      "source": "CDC STEADI medicines risk resource",
      "url": "https://www.cdc.gov/falls/about/index.html",
      "text": "\u6688, \u4f4e\u8840\u58d3, \u591a\u91cd\u7528\u85e5, \u526f\u4f5c\u7528, medicine, medication, sedative, dizziness, low blood pressure\nContent: Some medicines can increase sleepiness, dizziness, slower reaction time, orthostatic hypotension, or confusion, which may raise fall risk. Medicines to discuss with a clinician or pharmacist include sleep medicines, sedatives, anti-anxiety medicines, some pain medicines, some blood pressure medicines, antihistamines, and complex medication lists. Do not stop prescribed medicines without professional guidance.",
