    {
      "id": "doc-3-chunk-1",
      "document_id": "dehydration",
      "title": "Dehydration concerns in older adults",
      "source": "MedlinePlus emergency care guidance",
      "url": "https://medlineplus.gov/ency/patientinstructions/000593.htm",
      "text": "ds: \u812b\u6c34, \u559d\u6c34, \u8179\u7009, \u5614\u5410, \u767c\u71d2, \u5c3f\u5c11, \u865b\u5f31, dehydration, vomiting, diarrhea, fever, weakness\nContent: Older adults may need prompt medical evaluation when vomiting or diarrhea continues, fever is present, urine is much lower than usual, the mouth is very dry, dizziness occurs, weakness is severe, or mental status worsens. If symptoms are severe, the person cannot keep fluids down, or there is confusion or fainting, urgent care or emergency care may be needed.",
